@AdamLonghorn @MalachiRevolts @MaxY0rk Because not doing so fractures the mempool, and/or leads to more direct-to-miner transactions. It becomes a gate without a wall, ie useless.

But the beauty of bitcoin is that people can tweak their own nodes or run other versions.

The contiguous images in the blockchain are not .jpg or .pdf files anyway. It’s all broken up, just in different ways.

The data is still there. You think regulators that want to ban bitcoin won’t do so if there’s some minor technical nuance but all the data is still there?

As for suggestions, people have a lot of suggestions for bitcoin, but if it were easy to change (even to appeal to government regulators) then it wouldn’t be worth much.

Good luck.

@MalachiRevolts @MaxY0rk @hodlonaut It’s a global asset, not a security within any one jurisdiction.

But I support if you want to try to fork to what you perceive as a government-approved version. That’s your right. But the chance of it being successful in this form is vanishingly small.

